Here are some examples of these fiscal protection policies in developed and developing countries during these two crises. As the most important governmental policies for financial support during the GFC crisis, governments and central banks of developed countries, including the Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the Bank of England provided unprecedented trillions of dollars as bailouts and stimulus. These broad fiscal policies provide banks with good resources to offset the decline in consumption and lending capacity, avoid a further collapse, encourage lending, restore faith in the integral commercial paper markets, avoid the risk of a deflationary spiral, and provide banks with enough funds to allow customers to make withdrawals (
 Fleming, 2012; 
 French, 2009).
